Input:  S Select the best translation into predicate logic. Some kind people help some endangered species. (Ex: x is endangered; Kx: x is kind; Px: x is a person; Sx: x is a species; Hxy: x helps y) Choices: a) (∃x){(Kx • Px) • (∃y)(Ey • Sy) • Hxy} b) (∃x)(∃y){(Kx • Sx) • (Ey • Py) • Hxy} c) (∃x)(∃y){(Kx • Sx) • (Ey • Py) • Hyx} d) (∃x)(∃y){(Kx • Px) • (Ey • Sy) ⊃ Hxy} 
Output:
First, we need to identify the individuals and their properties. We have people (Px), kind people (Kx), endangered species (Ex), and species (Sx).
Next, we need to translate the verbs into logical connectives. "Help" is translated as Hxy, meaning x helps y.
Finally, we need to construct the sentence according to the given information. "Some kind people help some endangered species" can be translated as: There exists a kind person (Kx) who helps an endangered species (Ex).

Looking at the options, the best translation is: (∃x)(∃y){(Kx • Sx) • (Ey • Py) • Hxy}

{'sol': 'c'}
